# Scientific Calculator (HTML + CSS + JS + PHP)

A scientific calculator split across four files, with both instant client-side
calculation and an optional server-side (PHP) evaluation path.

## Files

| File            | Role                                                                 |
|-----------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `calc.php`     | Page shell / markup. Outputs the calculator HTML (PHP used for title, version, and to serve as the app's entry point). |
| `calc.css`     | All visual styling (dark theme, grid layout, responsive).            |
| `calc.js`     | UI logic + a safe recursive-descent expression parser/evaluator (no `eval()`). Handles button clicks, keyboard input, DEG/RAD toggle. |
| `calculate.php` | JSON API endpoint. Re-implements the same expression parser in PHP and evaluates the expression server-side when the **"PHP∑"** button is pressed. |

## Features

- Basic operations: `+ − × ÷`, decimals, parentheses
- Scientific functions: `sin`, `cos`, `tan`, `log` (base 10), `ln` (natural log), `√`, `x²`, `x^y`, `x!`, `1/x`
- Constants: `π`, `e`
- `%`, `±` (sign toggle)
- DEG / RAD angle mode toggle
- Keyboard support (digits, operators, Enter, Backspace, Escape)
- AC (clear all), CE (clear entry), ⌫ (backspace)
- **PHP∑** button: sends the current expression to `calculate.php` via `fetch()` and displays the server-computed result, proving the PHP backend is functioning independently of the JS evaluator.

## How to run

You need a PHP-capable web server for the PHP endpoint to work (plain file
opening via `file://` will not execute PHP).

**Option 1 — PHP built-in server (simplest):**

```bash
cd scientific-calculator
php -S localhost:8000
```

Then open `http://localhost:8000/index.php` in your browser.

**Option 2 — XAMPP / WAMP / MAMP / any Apache+PHP stack:**

Copy the `scientific-calculator` folder into your server's document root
(e.g. `htdocs/`) and visit `http://localhost/scientific-calculator/index.php`.

> Note: The calculator works fully client-side (instant results on `=`) even
> without PHP running — the PHP path is only used when you click **PHP∑**.